00:22:08,903 --> 00:22:21,101
So what he says of that, he says it's painful, tukko, he says it's painful, he says it's ignoble, and it's not connected with the goal.

193
00:22:21,121 --> 00:22:23,523
So he's trying to get this balanced.

194
00:22:23,544 --> 00:22:30,894
Now, we talk about the middle way, which he then goes on to explain.

195
00:22:31,246 --> 00:22:49,428
just to read it to you, not having approached either of these two extreme monks, the middle practice, the middle way, was awakened to by the realized one, by the Tathagata, which produces vision, produces knowledge, which leads to peace, deep knowledge, complete awakening and emancipation.

196
00:22:50,509 --> 00:22:59,920
Abhinyana means knowledge, Abhi means very great or very deep, probably could translate it as transcendent knowledge.

197
00:23:01,672 --> 00:23:03,556
Now, what is this middle way, monks?

198
00:23:03,816 --> 00:23:08,263
The awakened two has realized one, etc., etc., and that's the eightfold path.

199
00:23:08,684 --> 00:23:14,134
Now, when we say the middle way, you might think, well, it's a bit of moderation.

200
00:23:14,435 --> 00:23:17,260
You do a bit of this and a bit of that, and you're in the middle somewhere.

201
00:23:17,903 --> 00:23:22,431
But although it's called the middle way because...

202
00:23:22,663 --> 00:23:52,231
you are still enjoying life and you're not going into these self mortification things because it's a completely different psychology a completely different understanding it's the middle way doesn't quite middle doesn't quite get get to the root of it it's more I would have thought transcendent of those two paths and yet feeding into these two paths so on the one side you're still enjoying life

203
00:23:52,464 --> 00:23:54,768
but you're trying not to be attached to it.

204
00:23:55,189 --> 00:24:06,284
And on the other side, you're not self-mortifying yourself, you're not trying to blame the body for anything, but on the other hand, you are renouncing things that you see is not good for you.

205
00:24:07,465 --> 00:24:18,862
But it's coming from a different understanding about how we've got into this situation, which goes back to this business of identity and the self.

206
00:24:20,605 --> 00:24:22,287
Anyway, that's just a little side point.

207
00:24:23,059 --> 00:24:27,334
So then there's the Eightfold Path, which we'll come to in a bit.

208
00:24:31,890 --> 00:24:35,803
And then he goes through the actual Four Noble Truths.

209
00:24:36,661 --> 00:24:39,183
This discourse isn't verbatim, obviously.

210
00:24:39,223 --> 00:24:44,691
I mean, he wouldn't have come out with such a formula, such a formulated talk.

211
00:24:44,730 --> 00:24:48,776
I mean, you might think, well, he's been there under a tree for seven weeks.

212
00:24:49,236 --> 00:24:52,400
So he's got his talk in his head.

213
00:24:52,740 --> 00:24:54,102
Because remember, he's illiterate.

214
00:24:54,583 --> 00:24:56,404
It's very difficult for us to grasp that, isn't it?

215
00:24:56,424 --> 00:24:57,326
He's illiterate.

216
00:24:57,385 --> 00:24:58,647
People didn't read, didn't write.

217
00:24:58,988 --> 00:25:00,609
It was all memory stuff.

218
00:25:00,589 --> 00:25:25,737
but obviously he would have continued in a conversational mode and then later on the teaching becomes formalized and so this is a formalized teaching just laying the basis upon which all this teaching is based and that's why in a sense it can be called the turning of the wheel of the law

219
00:25:26,307 --> 00:25:41,666
there was a monk who actually suggested they put the symbol of the wheel on one of the doors of the monastery, on the top of the door of the monastery.

220
00:25:42,548 --> 00:25:50,137
So we have to see this discourse not so much as verbatim, in fact it's very difficult to say we have any of the original words of the Buddha,

221
00:25:50,589 --> 00:25:53,673
There are parts of the scriptures which are very, very old.

222
00:25:54,854 --> 00:25:56,776
But, of course, they developed as they went through.

223
00:25:56,816 --> 00:26:03,221
And what happened was that they would hear a talk.

224
00:26:03,301 --> 00:26:07,807
It would be systemized into ways of memory.

225
00:26:07,846 --> 00:26:09,208
That's why we've got so many lists.

226
00:26:10,048 --> 00:26:16,954
And then groups of monks would take responsibility for remembering certain groups of scriptures.

227
00:26:17,655 --> 00:26:19,617
They were called the barnacles, the reciters.

228
00:26:20,272 --> 00:26:27,580
So it would be very rare if there was ever one monk or nun who knew all the scriptures.

229
00:26:28,321 --> 00:26:33,646
So it depended on which group of monks you were with, the flavor of the teachings that you got.

230
00:26:34,567 --> 00:26:36,730
Because it's quite a collection when you think about it.

231
00:26:36,750 --> 00:26:45,640
So scholars, academics can see that there are different levels in the Pali, in the way the Pali is structured.

232
00:26:46,243 --> 00:26:51,529
So Bhikkhu Bodhi has just translated the Nipata Sutta, which is one of the earliest strata.

233
00:26:52,130 --> 00:26:53,791
It's a great big book.

234
00:26:54,353 --> 00:26:57,296
Which isn't such a collection of discourses.

235
00:26:57,336 --> 00:27:03,241
It's not such a big collection, but he's added all the commentarial stuff to it.

236
00:27:03,261 --> 00:27:05,884
Included in that are the two chants that we do in the evening.

237
00:27:06,065 --> 00:27:11,391
The loving-kindness one and the, sorry, the morning loving-kindness one.

238
00:27:11,657 --> 00:27:14,780
and the Mangala Sutta, the blessings.

239
00:27:15,320 --> 00:27:16,721
That comes from that strata too.

240
00:27:16,982 --> 00:27:22,626
So also they would create verse, which would make it easy to remember.

241
00:27:25,309 --> 00:27:34,376
So we have to see this discourse as really turning the wheel of the law in the sense that it's the platform upon which all his teaching is based.

242
00:27:34,396 --> 00:27:39,402
So he starts off now by saying, look, this monks is the noble truth of suffering.

243
00:27:40,021 --> 00:27:41,022
Now,

244
00:27:41,662 --> 00:27:44,767
Birth is suffering, old age is suffering, sickness is suffering.

245
00:27:45,347 --> 00:27:47,931
Death is also suffering.

246
00:27:52,818 --> 00:27:58,928
Getting what you don't want is suffering and being separated from what is dear to you is suffering.

247
00:28:01,067 --> 00:28:03,832
Not obtaining what one longs for is suffering.

248
00:28:04,291 --> 00:28:09,700
In short, the five grasping candor is suffering.

249
00:28:10,099 --> 00:28:18,632
So now, here in the discourse, we have the first way that he looks at the human being through these five aggregates.

250
00:28:19,752 --> 00:28:21,455
And there's a purpose to it, of course.

251
00:28:22,237 --> 00:28:26,241
The first one is the body and how the mind experiences the body.

252
00:28:26,982 --> 00:28:30,567
So that's the primary sensations that you feel.

253
00:28:30,970 --> 00:28:32,250
Heat, cold, etc.

254
00:28:33,692 --> 00:28:39,519
And then there's feeling, where we distinguish between what's pleasant and unpleasant.

255
00:28:40,118 --> 00:28:42,461
That's a natural process within us.

256
00:28:42,902 --> 00:28:43,682
You can't stop it.

257
00:28:44,242 --> 00:28:50,690
As soon as you feel something, we judge it to be either pleasant or unpleasant.

258
00:28:50,769 --> 00:28:51,851
This isn't a bad judging.

259
00:28:51,891 --> 00:28:54,353
This is just the way we are in the world.

260
00:28:56,154 --> 00:28:58,917
And then there's perception, which moves into memory.

261
00:28:59,371 --> 00:29:04,018
And also those feelings, remember, include the feelings caused in the body by mental states.

262
00:29:04,538 --> 00:29:07,142
And then we have these volitional conditionings.

263
00:29:07,162 --> 00:29:10,707
And then finally consciousness, which is the screen upon which everything happens.

264
00:29:10,767 --> 00:29:12,809
It's a multidimensional screen.

265
00:29:13,009 --> 00:29:16,275
Everything you experience is flashing on that screen.

266
00:29:17,896 --> 00:29:28,332
So what he's pointing to there is the volitional conditionings which we actually are developing, producing.

267
00:29:28,835 --> 00:29:43,603
our habits that's the best word I've come across for it just our habits the way we reinforce certain patterns of behaviour patterns of thinking etc and some of them are wholesome some of them aren't you see

268
00:29:44,815 --> 00:29:48,561
But he says it's the clinging nature of these.

269
00:29:48,741 --> 00:29:54,432
It's the way we cling to this psychophysical organism.

270
00:29:54,551 --> 00:29:55,413
That's what it amounts to.

271
00:29:56,234 --> 00:30:00,001
Is what is suffering.

272
00:30:00,663 --> 00:30:02,205
The clinging.

273
00:30:02,546 --> 00:30:03,307
That's really important.

274
00:30:03,347 --> 00:30:07,674
If I give another talk on dependent origination.

275
00:30:07,955 --> 00:30:09,117
Remember that.

276
00:30:09,232 --> 00:30:17,271
There's the feeling, there's the reaction to it of not wanting it or trying to overcome it.

277
00:30:18,193 --> 00:30:21,240
And then there's the identity, I don't want.

278
00:30:21,903 --> 00:30:27,916
And what we've got to really grasp is that the suffering doesn't start until the point of identity.

279
00:30:28,251 --> 00:30:44,530
which is often, it's a difficult point to really grasp because when you're in yourself and something horrible is coming up and you can feel the negativity, it's difficult to realise that actually you've separated out of it.

280
00:30:45,111 --> 00:30:53,601
And it's only when that separation becomes more and more obvious that you realise that actually there is this gunk going on, but there is no suffering as such.

281
00:30:54,374 --> 00:30:58,059
And that's a different quality when you suddenly say, I can't handle this.

282
00:30:59,323 --> 00:31:01,666
And then you drop into it, as it were.

283
00:31:02,248 --> 00:31:03,971
And that's the point of suffering.

284
00:31:03,990 --> 00:31:10,761
So that's why he doesn't say the five desiring candors.

285
00:31:10,781 --> 00:31:15,931
He says the five grasping candors, the ones that we grasp with a sense of self.

286
00:31:16,873 --> 00:31:16,972
Yeah.

287
00:31:24,326 --> 00:31:32,257
There is, at the same time, in other discourses, there is a different description of dukkha.

288
00:31:32,738 --> 00:31:40,366
So this word dukkha, that's the root word upon which he builds everything, this dukkha, which just means hard to bear.

289
00:31:41,588 --> 00:31:52,241
First of all, there is that dukkha, dukkhata, just the pain, the suffering that we engender because of the unsatisfactoriness of the body and mind.

290
00:31:53,065 --> 00:32:05,519
Then there's the suffering that arises because of the fact that everything we experience is a compendium.

291
00:32:05,539 --> 00:32:07,843
It's a conjunction of things.

292
00:32:09,005 --> 00:32:09,885
It's an imminence.

293
00:32:09,905 --> 00:32:14,250
It's where all these little bits and pieces come together to create something.

294
00:32:15,071 --> 00:32:16,855
And so nothing has any reality.

295
00:32:16,914 --> 00:32:18,656
Nothing has any substance to itself.

296
00:32:18,737 --> 00:32:21,299
Everything is dependent on something else.

297
00:32:21,397 --> 00:32:46,511
and just contemplating the body and that it's made up of these billions of cells which can all you know go their own way if they want and that's the end of it you begin to recognize that everything is it doesn't have that substantiality that we we think it has or we experience it as yeah and then of course there's a suffering that comes from change

298
00:32:46,811 --> 00:33:07,790
you can't just stop you can't say well this is it this is what I've always been looking for stop the world it doesn't happen so those are your three types of suffering just the ordinary suffering of life and what not which includes sickness, ageing and death there's a suffering that comes because there's nothing substantial in us

299
00:33:07,770 --> 00:33:19,738
There's nothing we can hold on to and say, well, this is truly me of the psychophysical organism and everything that we experience is constantly changing.

300
00:33:23,751 --> 00:33:28,538
So that's how he describes the noble truth of suffering.

301
00:33:29,601 --> 00:33:35,890
Then there comes the second one, the noble truth of the arising of suffering, samudaya, the arising of suffering.

302
00:33:36,230 --> 00:33:39,275
And now he's pointing to this word tanha.

303
00:33:39,295 --> 00:33:43,320
So remember, there's another word in Pali, chanda, which means desire.

304
00:33:44,102 --> 00:33:45,523
And that can be good or bad.

305
00:33:46,184 --> 00:33:51,413
So it's your motivation, it's your intention which makes it good or bad.

306
00:33:51,747 --> 00:34:00,457
But the word tanna is a specific word which refers to desires which just lead to suffering one way or the other.

307
00:34:01,218 --> 00:34:08,885
And so you get other translations for it like thirst, lack, a lack.

308
00:34:08,905 --> 00:34:19,998
Remember desire comes out of a state of unsatisfactoriness at some level or other and is itself a state of suffering.

309
00:34:20,400 --> 00:34:22,565
To be in a state of desire is not a pleasant state.

310
00:34:23,126 --> 00:34:28,237
It only becomes a pleasant state when we see the end of the desire, that it's going to be satisfied or gratified.

311
00:34:29,239 --> 00:34:31,304
If it's not, then it's a state of suffering.

312
00:34:31,905 --> 00:34:35,894
So desire comes out of suffering and is itself a state of suffering.

313
00:34:35,976 --> 00:34:39,561
Suffering here used in the widest sense, unsatisfactoriness.

314
00:34:40,702 --> 00:34:43,806
That's the other thing too, that dukkha used to be translated as suffering.

315
00:34:44,646 --> 00:34:46,469
And then of course people said, well I don't suffer.

316
00:34:48,050 --> 00:34:50,572
Meaning that they were having a good life at that time.

317
00:34:51,974 --> 00:34:57,440
So they had to find another word for it and they came up with unsatisfactoriness.

318
00:34:57,481 --> 00:35:00,043
And that's the other side, remember, that I always keep pumping.

319
00:35:00,324 --> 00:35:04,548
This business of how indulgence in pleasure

320
00:35:05,996 --> 00:35:11,864
has its comeuppance.

321
00:35:11,884 --> 00:35:12,505
So...

322
00:35:14,786 --> 00:35:17,791
Yes, he says desire is the cause of suffering.

323
00:35:17,811 --> 00:35:19,192
The craving for sense pleasure.

324
00:35:19,773 --> 00:35:22,896
And he divides it now, this tanha, into three types.

325
00:35:22,936 --> 00:35:27,202
The craving for sense pleasure, karma tanha, bhava tanha, vibhava tanha.

326
00:35:27,222 --> 00:35:28,623
Craving for continuation.

327
00:35:29,063 --> 00:35:31,726
And the craving for discontinuation.

328
00:35:31,746 --> 00:35:32,527
Now...

329
00:35:32,795 --> 00:35:40,487
Karmatana, the desire for sense pleasures, that's, well we know that, that's sincere enough.

330
00:35:40,987 --> 00:35:47,036
Bhavatana is the desire to make it continue, but it's also the desire to keep becoming.

331
00:35:47,597 --> 00:35:57,132
So it both refers to the desire of trying to maintain a certain pleasure as best you can, but it's also referring to the self-wanting pleasure.

332
00:35:57,313 --> 00:35:59,938
The self wants to continue, wants to keep living.

333
00:36:00,798 --> 00:36:02,402
And the same with Vibhavatana.

334
00:36:02,422 --> 00:36:06,547
Vibhavatana refers to the fact of wanting to get rid of what you don't want.

335
00:36:06,929 --> 00:36:08,210
That's sort of aversion to it.

336
00:36:08,572 --> 00:36:11,976
But it also refers to wanting to get rid of yourself.

337
00:36:12,777 --> 00:36:21,731
Either you're just fed up and bored and depressed and you dive under the duvet or something.

338
00:36:22,293 --> 00:36:24,856
Or you actually want to make your way to a bridge or something.

339
00:36:28,280 --> 00:36:41,324
Whenever I say that, I always remind this lovely clip that I had from a comedian, I can't remember his name now, but he's extremely funny, around about the 50s, something like that.

340
00:36:41,344 --> 00:36:46,255
And he meets this, he's going to jump off a bridge in London, off the Westminster Bridge.

341
00:36:47,483 --> 00:36:48,603
And a copper comes.

342
00:36:48,623 --> 00:36:50,626
He says, excuse me, sir.

343
00:36:50,646 --> 00:36:53,050
He says, you know, you mustn't do that.

344
00:36:53,389 --> 00:36:57,474
And they have this sort of argument about life and all that sort of stuff.

345
00:36:57,494 --> 00:36:59,637
And the sketch ends when they both jump off the bridge.

346
00:37:02,201 --> 00:37:06,927
It was really funny.

347
00:37:06,947 --> 00:37:08,869
So, yes, that's the bhava.

348
00:37:10,030 --> 00:37:12,373
Sorry, the tanha, right?

349
00:37:12,393 --> 00:37:17,119
Sense pleasures, always wanting to maintain, wanting to continue, wanting to live

350
00:37:17,487 --> 00:37:20,530
wanting to get rid of Vibhavatana.

351
00:37:20,550 --> 00:37:34,750
I mean, these are pointing us to actually investigate in our practice, you know, to actually name it and say, oh, that's an aversion, and that's me being averse to myself, I want to get rid of myself at this present time.

352
00:37:35,391 --> 00:37:42,199
So it's just being aware of these, it's just pointing to certain mental habits that we have.

353
00:37:44,643 --> 00:37:47,206
And then, of course, he makes this great statement, he says that

354
00:37:47,507 --> 00:37:49,713
There is a noble truth of the cessation of suffering.

355
00:37:49,753 --> 00:37:55,065
He says it's the complete fading away, the cessation without remainder of that craving.

356
00:37:55,507 --> 00:37:59,757
It's the liberation, the letting go, the release and non-adherence.

357
00:38:01,360 --> 00:38:05,010
So that's a really very...

358
00:38:05,480 --> 00:38:34,085
direct statement there's no pulling back on that statement it's not as though uh say modern psychotherapies might say well you know you can get to a decent accommodation with life you can sort of be generally content and whatnot but here he makes i don't know of any psychotherapist that says that there's a complete end to suffering here and now not i mean a lot of religions will point to the afterlife you know like you're working at it now and then you know you get to the gates and

359
00:38:34,471 --> 00:38:57,880
and you're away but this statement is right here and now and of course you find the same in Hinduism of course that liberation is right here and now if we work hard enough for it or if we want it enough so that brings us to now the path itself

360
00:38:58,871 --> 00:38:59,592
The Eightfold Path.

361
00:38:59,934 --> 00:39:11,170
Now, the normal way that it's written down is, of course, right view, right attitude, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, right concentration.

362
00:39:11,570 --> 00:39:23,748
But it's normally taught in the division of Sila Samadhi Panya, which is moral, ethical, ethic life, your development of meditation, and then the wisdom comes from it, you see.

363
00:39:24,286 --> 00:39:34,565
So now this actually brings it, looking at it that way, actually brings it to, I think, a correct view of how to approach our lives.

364
00:39:35,186 --> 00:39:49,623
coming back from the way that the Buddha, that is put here, there is this great misunderstanding that lies within us, this delusion about who we are, or what it is, or however you want to phrase it.

365
00:39:50,344 --> 00:39:55,490
And because of that, we make a sort of bargain with life.

366
00:39:55,610 --> 00:40:02,659
We say, well look, this is it, this is the way it is, so I'm now going to try and make the best I can of this life, seeking happiness there.

367
00:40:03,039 --> 00:40:04,722
So remember, that's our...

368
00:40:04,920 --> 00:40:06,822
That's the platform that we're working off.

369
00:40:06,922 --> 00:40:07,784
We're not working off.

370
00:40:09,085 --> 00:40:12,847
Nobody works off even the most horrible characters in history.

371
00:40:13,088 --> 00:40:14,949
They're not working off the platform I hate.

372
00:40:15,030 --> 00:40:17,371
They're working off the platform of I want to be happy.

373
00:40:18,293 --> 00:40:22,556
If that I want to be happy moves towards, well, for me to be happy, I've got to hate you.

374
00:40:23,157 --> 00:40:25,159
And that's the way it moves.

375
00:40:25,760 --> 00:40:31,144
But our basic human nature right down at that basic is we're actually seeking happiness.

376
00:40:31,445 --> 00:40:33,746
Everybody's trying to seek happiness one way or the other.

377
00:40:34,469 --> 00:40:45,003
And because of this wrong understanding, of course, we form a wrong relationship with the world, thinking that if I accumulate things, that's going to make me happy.

378
00:40:45,043 --> 00:40:45,844
So there's your greed.

379
00:40:46,525 --> 00:40:49,630
And then you've got to defend it because somebody else wants your accumulation.

380
00:40:49,650 --> 00:40:54,657
And if whoever wants your accumulation is bigger than you, we've got to run for it.

381
00:40:54,978 --> 00:41:04,391
So those three things, acquisitiveness, aversion and fear, are right at the base manifesting this wrong understanding.

382
00:41:04,760 --> 00:41:20,960
So the way that we behave from this wrong understanding, we're not always behaving from wrong understanding, but the way we're behaving from wrong understanding is the way back to undermining that wrong understanding.

383
00:41:21,561 --> 00:41:31,155
So it's by living ethically, looking at our moral lives, being careful about what we allow the mind to get caught up in,

384
00:41:31,556 --> 00:42:00,922
or what we indulge the mind with that's the way back as it were to the original problem because as you come back you can feel the energies that are based on this delusion you know renouncing something that renunciation gives you an inkling of how much you are attached to what you want to give up yeah when you're with somebody whom there's a natural aversion for

385
00:42:01,561 --> 00:42:07,349
then you're with that part of you that doesn't want to be with anything which is upsetting.

386
00:42:08,451 --> 00:42:13,938
And when you're in a frightening situation, a situation that causes anxiety, you're coming back from it.

387
00:42:14,318 --> 00:42:30,302
So by working with our ethical life, by working with our moral lives, which manifests in these attitudes, mental states, emotional states, we're actually coming back to the original problems.

388
00:42:30,652 --> 00:42:43,971
which is the identity and at base the last guard against undoing that delusion is fear

389
00:42:45,722 --> 00:42:47,686
See, the loss of identity.

390
00:42:47,786 --> 00:42:48,385
Who are you?

391
00:42:48,586 --> 00:42:49,748
You know, and all that sort of stuff.

392
00:42:51,010 --> 00:42:57,878
And that we come close to whenever we are struck by a serious illness or eventually our death.

393
00:42:58,440 --> 00:43:01,123
That's when we'll hit that point.

394
00:43:01,764 --> 00:43:07,952
And the fear and the aversion that arises for that is the measure of this delusion.

395
00:43:08,612 --> 00:43:08,693
See?

396
00:43:09,398 --> 00:43:23,096
So I always think rather than our meditation, always trying to think about attaining something, some sort of insight, some great explosive experience that's going to change my life.

397
00:43:24,416 --> 00:43:33,688
You're far better off working with the negativity within us because there you can eventually begin to see some results.

398
00:43:34,230 --> 00:43:37,414
And as the heart begins to purify itself,

399
00:43:37,630 --> 00:43:59,992
this intelligence, this satipanya, this intuitive awareness is clearer, because remember, the delusion lies in looking, it doesn't lie in the body, the body's not deluded, the body's just the body, it doesn't lie within the heart, the heart's just feeling, that's all it is, it's only because we personalize it, it's only because I say, I am angry, or I am

400
00:44:00,309 --> 00:44:29,963
afraid that it becomes a sense of me, the heart is just feeling, that's all it is, feeling and the head is just thinking imagining so the delusion isn't there they are manifestations of delusion the delusion lies in this satipanya itself, in other words it's the Buddha himself within us which is deluded so it's coming back on that where we can begin to have little insights as to

401
00:44:30,230 --> 00:44:38,840
as to this business of how we create suffering, how we imagine things are going to last when nothing lasts at all.

402
00:44:39,922 --> 00:44:49,954
And how we give things concrete, how we stabilize things, how we conceptualize things into some sort of reality which we presume will continue.

403
00:44:50,476 --> 00:44:57,063
So all that begins to be undermined when we actually begin to look at our ethical lives.

404
00:44:59,288 --> 00:45:03,056
So that's produced as right speech, of course, right attitude.

405
00:45:03,617 --> 00:45:05,943
He's translated right thought here.

406
00:45:05,963 --> 00:45:08,007
But it's more right attitude, I think.

407
00:45:08,027 --> 00:45:10,291
Right speech, right action, right livelihood.

408
00:45:10,311 --> 00:45:16,284
Don't forget our livelihood, what we do for most of the day, has a conditioning effect on us.

409
00:45:17,260 --> 00:45:24,750
Then there's the meditation itself, which is what we're doing here, the vipassana.

410
00:45:25,429 --> 00:45:27,893
And then the insights come, the samaditi.

411
00:45:29,094 --> 00:45:35,884
So if you look at your practice as sila samadhi panya, I think it moves much more easily.

412
00:45:36,284 --> 00:45:39,969
We don't feel so frustrated about not attaining something.

413
00:45:41,590 --> 00:45:44,635
Just allow that to happen as the purity grows.

414
00:45:46,588 --> 00:45:55,603
Anyway, once he'd done this, there's this lovely PM now.

415
00:46:01,760 --> 00:46:08,465
Then he goes into the three modes of each of these noble truths.

416
00:46:08,565 --> 00:46:14,911
The first mode is that there is suffering.

417
00:46:14,931 --> 00:46:16,572
It's just a bold statement.

418
00:46:16,592 --> 00:46:18,494
There is the noble truth of suffering.

419
00:46:19,014 --> 00:46:22,077
And then he says that this ought to be known.

420
00:46:22,978 --> 00:46:23,998
It ought to be known.

421
00:46:24,039 --> 00:46:27,961
It ought to be understood what he means by suffering.

422
00:46:28,422 --> 00:46:31,125
And then he tells us that he has fully understood it.

423
00:46:31,695 --> 00:46:35,420
And then he talks about the arising of suffering, the cause of suffering.

424
00:46:35,440 --> 00:46:37,242
And he says that this ought to be given up.

425
00:46:37,483 --> 00:46:41,708
So this is where academics become, I think, a little silly.

426
00:46:42,088 --> 00:46:44,833
Because it says the noble truth of desire has to be given up.

427
00:46:44,873 --> 00:46:46,775
So how can you give up a noble truth?

428
00:46:48,777 --> 00:46:50,699
But it's shorthand, isn't it?

429
00:46:50,719 --> 00:46:55,206
It's shorthand for it is true to say that we ought to give up desire, you know.

430
00:46:56,215 --> 00:47:22,864
never mind so and then he says that he has given it up see it has been given up then there's a cessation of suffering which has which ought to be realized and he has realized it and then finally the path leading to it which ought to be developed and that he has developed it fully so we ought to be moving to those final statements that you know we have overcome desire

431
00:47:23,130 --> 00:47:33,579
we have attained Nibbana and we have practiced the path to its end.

432
00:47:40,393 --> 00:47:46,181
So when to me monks in regard to these four noble truths turned like this in three ways.

433
00:47:46,882 --> 00:47:48,844
So that's also this idea of a wheel.

434
00:47:49,864 --> 00:47:50,925
Wheel within wheels.

435
00:47:52,427 --> 00:47:58,655
Especially in the Abhidhamma you'll find this word vata coming up all the time.

436
00:47:59,115 --> 00:48:01,878
There are little wheels within wheels.

437
00:48:01,858 --> 00:48:07,108
Little ways like that one in Dependent Origination is an internal wheel, you see.

438
00:48:07,568 --> 00:48:15,302
The feeling, the desire, the tanha, and then the grasping.

439
00:48:17,186 --> 00:48:18,989
It revolves around each other.

440
00:48:20,742 --> 00:48:23,643
Knowledge and insight, as it really is, was quite clear.

441
00:48:23,724 --> 00:48:36,856
Then, monks, I did declare to the world with its gods, Mara and Brahma, to this generation with its ascetics and brahmanas, princes and men, that I was the fully and perfect Asambuddho with unsurpassed complete awakening.

442
00:48:37,255 --> 00:48:39,358
To me, knowledge and insight arose.

443
00:48:39,717 --> 00:48:41,440
Sure is my liberation of mind.

444
00:48:41,760 --> 00:48:43,121
This is my last birth.

445
00:48:43,501 --> 00:48:45,762
Now there is no more continuation.

446
00:48:46,583 --> 00:48:48,324
That's a lovely statement, right?

447
00:48:48,344 --> 00:48:50,327
You can imagine him saying that, you know, it's just...

448
00:48:51,320 --> 00:48:56,612
If you said that here in this room, we'd all go, oh yeah.

449
00:48:56,632 --> 00:49:09,463
So then there's this lovely paean that says, the master sweet of the truth, sorry, hearing these words, the earth deities, all the gods in the universe,

450
00:49:09,864 --> 00:49:29,072
Heaven of the Four Kings, the matchless wheel, this was heard say, the matchless wheel of the truth that cannot be set in motion by a recluse, by a Brahmana, a Deva, a God, a Mara, a Brahma, anyone in this world is set in motion by the Blessed One at the Deer Park at Isipatana near Varanasi.

451
00:49:29,092 --> 00:49:33,780
And these words were heard in the upper Deva realms, in the Chattu Maharajika realms.

452
00:49:33,760 --> 00:49:58,501
in the tabata tabata timsa and it goes all the way through these all these heavens to the mahabrama the paritabab the apamanaba there's a whole load of them and then and and this cry goes up it's a lovely sort of image all the way through these realms from the lowest right up to the heavens and it says the matchless wheel of truth that cannot be set in motion by a recluse or a brahman

453
00:49:58,751 --> 00:50:06,498
or a Deva, or a Mara, or a Brahma, or anyone in this world, is set in motion by the Blessed One and the Deoparkat, Isipata and Ibn Aris.

454
00:50:08,079 --> 00:50:27,577
Thus, at that very moment, at that instant, the cry that the wheel of truth had been set in motion spread as far as the Brahma realm, and the system of ten thousand worlds trembled and quaked and shook, and a boundless, a boundless sublime radiance, surpassing the effulgence of the gods, appeared in the world.

455
00:50:28,570 --> 00:50:31,114
And then the Blessed One uttered this peon of joy.

456
00:50:31,856 --> 00:50:34,382
Verily Kondanya has realized.

457
00:50:34,402 --> 00:50:37,628
Verily Kondanya has realized.

458
00:50:38,028 --> 00:50:42,478
The Venerable Kondanya then receives the name Anya Kondanya.

459
00:50:42,677 --> 00:50:44,802
So there was one of his companions who got it.

460
00:50:47,588 --> 00:50:49,532
So that's how this lovely...

461
00:50:50,322 --> 00:51:18,911
discourse ends with this wonderful sort of image of it rising of the wheel of the teaching rising up through all the heavens and get to the top and then he finally acknowledges that this old companion of his has now become fully liberated so I can only hope this has not confused you or anything but has inspired you to devote yourself entirely to the practice for liberation awaits us

462
00:51:20,478 --> 00:51:27,701
May you be fully liberated from all suffering.

463
00:51:29,246 --> 00:51:33,659
Sooner rather than later.

